<div class="bg-zinc-950 text-zinc-100">
  <.marketing_nav current_user={@current_user} current={:docs} />

  <section class="py-16 sm:py-24">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 lg:px-8">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-indigo-400">Compare</p>
      <.marketing_heading tag="h1" scale={:hero} class="mt-2">
        Why not just give the LLM SSH?
      </.marketing_heading>
      <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-8 text-zinc-400">
        The honest answer: you can. Some people do. It works on the days it works.
        Here's what changes when it doesn't.
      </p>

      <h2 class="mt-12 text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">Both approaches run real commands</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-zinc-400">
        emisar isn't a sandbox. When the runner executes <code>nodetool repair</code>, it really repairs the keyspace — exactly like
        SSH would. The difference is what happens <em>before</em> exec, and what's
        left <em>after</em>.
      </p>

      <h2 class="mt-10 text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">Side-by-side</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border border-zinc-900">
        <table class="min-w-[680px] text-sm">
          <thead class="bg-zinc-950/80 text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-zinc-500">
            <tr>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left">Concern</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left">Raw SSH</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left">emisar action pack</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-zinc-900 text-zinc-300">
            <tr>
              <td class="px-4 py-3">What can the LLM run?</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3">Anything in the user's shell</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3">Only declared actions; everything else rejected</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="px-4 py-3">What are the args?</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3">Free-text command line</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3">Typed, validated, redacted at the boundary</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="px-4 py-3">What actually ran?</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3">Whatever was on <code>PATH</code> that day</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3">
                Content-addressed pack — the runner recomputes the SHA-256 and blocks changed
                contents until an admin re-trusts
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="px-4 py-3">Approvals?</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3">Human-in-the-loop in chat — easy to skip</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3">
                Policy gates with approver email + audit; skipping means a policy change, itself
                audited
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="px-4 py-3">Audit trail?</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3">
                Whatever lands in <code>.bash_history</code> + Slack scrollback
              </td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3">Hash-chained JSONL on host, mirrored to cloud</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="px-4 py-3">Output redaction?</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3">None — passwords leak into chat logs</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3">
                20+ patterns (bearer/JWT, AWS/GitHub/Slack keys, secret assignments) masked on the
                host before egress
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="px-4 py-3">Lateral movement?</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3">SSH key on the model's box ≈ key everywhere</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3">
                Per-runner token + per-user runner scopes every API key inherits — revoke the
                user, every key they minted shrinks
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="px-4 py-3">Recovery story?</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3">"Read the chat scrollback and the logs and hope"</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3">
                <code>emisar audit verify</code> + replay every dispatched envelope
              </td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2 class="mt-10 text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">When raw SSH is the right answer</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-zinc-400">
        Single-operator side projects, throwaway environments, dev clusters
        you can wipe. The cost of declaring an action pack only pays back
        when there's <em>another human</em> who needs to audit, override, or
        recover from the AI's decisions.
      </p>

      <h2 class="mt-10 text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">When it isn't</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-zinc-400">
        Production. Anything regulated. Anything where post-incident your
        VP of Engineering will ask "what did the model do, exactly, and on
        whose authority?". That's the question raw SSH can't answer without
        a forensic budget. emisar makes the answer a query.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-12 rounded-xl border border-indigo-900/40 bg-indigo-950/20 p-5 text-sm text-zinc-300">
        Try it: install the runner from the <.link
          navigate={~p"/docs/quickstart"}
          class="text-indigo-400 hover:text-indigo-300"
        >quickstart</.link>, declare one action you'd otherwise SSH for, and point your model at
        it. The
        <.link navigate={~p"/pricing"} class="text-indigo-400 hover:text-indigo-300">
          free tier
        </.link>
        covers 3 runners — no credit card.
      </div>

      <div class="mt-8 flex flex-wrap gap-x-6 gap-y-3 border-t border-zinc-900 pt-8 text-sm">
        <.link
          navigate={~p"/docs/security-model"}
          class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 font-medium text-indigo-400 hover:text-indigo-300"
        >
          How the trust boundary works <.icon name="hero-arrow-right" class="h-3.5 w-3.5" />
        </.link>
        <.link
          navigate={~p"/docs/connect-an-llm"}
          class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 font-medium text-indigo-400 hover:text-indigo-300"
        >
          Connect your model <.icon name="hero-arrow-right" class="h-3.5 w-3.5" />
        </.link>
        <.link
          navigate={~p"/use-cases/cassandra-ops"}
          class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 font-medium text-indigo-400 hover:text-indigo-300"
        >
          See it on a Cassandra incident <.icon name="hero-arrow-right" class="h-3.5 w-3.5" />
        </.link>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <.marketing_cta
    headline="Stop handing AI agents raw SSH."
    subcopy="The same real commands — declared, policy-gated, approval-checked, and journaled. Recovery you're not betting your weekend on."
    secondary_label="Read the quickstart"
    secondary_path={~p"/docs/quickstart"}
  />

  <.marketing_footer />
</div>
